Complete Topic: Anticolonial Thought in the Caribbean
The various struggles that were directed against European colonialism around the world during the nineteenth and twentieth centuries were informed by a critical and diverse intellectual practice. In this course, we will focus on anticolonial thought in the Spanish-, English-, and French-speaking Caribbean by reading some key texts by thinkers, writers, activists, and militants who were involved in these struggles, including José Martí, Fernando Ortiz, C.L.R. James, Eric Williams, Aimé Césaire, and Frantz Fanon.


Texts:
- José Martí, Our America: Writings on Latin America and the Struggle for Cuban Independence (Monthly Review Press, 1977), ISBN 978-0853454953;
- Fernando Ortiz, Cuban Counterpoint: Tobacco and Sugar (Duke University Press, 1995), ISBN 978-0822316169;
- C.L.R. James, The Black Jacobins: Toussaint L'Ouverture and the San Domingo Revolution, rev. ed. (Vintage Books, 1989), ISBN 978-0679724674;
- Eric Williams, Capitalism and Slavery (University of North Carolina Press, 1994), ISBN 978-0807844885;
- Aimé Césaire, Notebook of a Return to the Native Land (Wesleyan University Press, 2001), ISBN 978-0819564528;
- Frantz Fanon, Black Skin, White Masks (Grove Press, 2008), ISBN 978-0802143006;
- Frantz Fanon, The Wretched of the Earth (Grove Press, 2005), ISBN 978-0802141323.


Assessment:
- Four (4) response papers (3-4 pp. each, 40% total);
- Long essay (12-16 pp., 40%);
- Attendance and participation (20%).
